    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.21-22_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">21</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Bushnell, Illinois
                        October, 16, 1957.
                    </dateline>
              
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Sir:-</salute></opener> <p>On Aug. 24, I read with great interest the article "Buckskin <add>and</add> Blanket Days" written by Thomas Henry Tibbles, and in the Saturday Evening Post of Oct 12. I read your article that you were acquainted with Thomas Henry Tibbles.</p>
                
                <p>I am of the opinion that Thomas Henry Tibbles was my husbands great uncle. My husbands grandmother <add>was</add> Eliza Tibbles Cole she married James Cole a banker in Bushnell, Illinois they are both dead. Grandmother Cole had told me many times about her brother running away from home + joining up with the Indians. She also told me her brother married and Indian girl and then her brother ran for Vice Pres. of the <hi rend="caps">U.S.</hi> but was beaten on account of being a radical. To my knowledge she never told
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.21-22_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">22</fw>
                
                    me her brothers name.</p>
                
                <p>There was a large Tibbles family
                    <list>
                        <item>Eliza Tibbles Cole &#8212; married James Cole</item>
                        <item>Laura    "     Hunter       " a man from Macomb, Ill.</item> 
                        <item>Lucy     "    _______</item>
                        <item>Mary     "    _______</item>
                        <item>Harvey   "   a Methodist minister near Chicago</item>
                        <item>Charles <hi rend="caps">E.</hi> Tibbles &#8212; an inventor lived in Chicago had 3 children <hi rend="underline">all deceased.</hi></item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                
                <p>Did you ever hear <del>of</del> Mr. Tibbles tell of any of the above. All of the above Tibbles people are deceased. Eliza Tibbles Cole and Laura Tibbles Hunter are both buried here, I am just curious to get any information that I can pass on to the next generation and anxious to know whether or not Thomas Henry Tibbles was related to my husbands grandmother. This would make Thomas Henry Tibbles my husbands great uncle. My sister-in-law from North Carolina wrote me about your article in Sat. Post. Thanking you for any information my husband passed away in 1947.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Mr. Charles E. Henry</signed>
                    <address><addrLine>Bushnell, Ill. 496 Rile St.</addrLine></address>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="letterhead"><hi rend="caps">BUY WAR BONDS AND STAMPS</hi></fw>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
